<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
The description is based on the pinned 
<typeStatus>holotype</typeStatus>
. The colour of the head changed from bright red into dark reddish brown after it died (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–19" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 17 - 19. 17 habitus of holotype. ♀ Megischus kuafu Ge &amp; Tan, sp. nov. (except ovipositor and ovipositor sheath) 18 ovipositor and ovipositor sheath 19 collecting living specimen." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1022.62833.figures17-19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/517765" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">19</figureCitation>
). The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Brulle, 1846" authorityName="Brulle" authorityYear="1846" class="Insecta" family="Stephanidae" genus="Megischus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megischus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Megischus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains the largest known stephanids and some of them can be up to 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" unit="mm" value="35.0">35 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4838.1.1" author="Binoy, C" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" pagination="1 - 51" refId="B7" refString="Binoy, C, van Achterberg, C, Girish Kumar, P, Santhoshi, S, Sheela, S, 2020. A review of Stephanidae (Hymenoptera: Stephanoidea) from India, with the description of five new species. Zootaxa 4838 (1): 1 - 51, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4838.1.1" title="A review of Stephanidae (Hymenoptera: Stephanoidea) from India, with the description of five new species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4838.1.1" volume="4838" year="2020">Binoy et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Although the size of parasitoids varies among specimens of the same species due to the nutritional conditions of the host and other factors, the body length of 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9" unit="mm" value="39.0">39 mm</quantity>
makes 
<taxonomicName family="Stephanidae" genus="M." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. kuafu" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="kuafu">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">M. kuafu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the largest known 
<taxonomicName authority="Brulle, 1846" authorityName="Brulle" authorityYear="1846" class="Insecta" family="Stephanidae" genus="Megischus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megischus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Megischus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen, and also the largest 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Stephanidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Stephanidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
